She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

I want to learn about social work. My goal is to help children who have been hurt or neglected. I also want to help families who are having problems. Important values for social workers include service, respect, and doing what is right. I want to use these values to help people and improve my skills so I can be good at my job.

I have always wanted to help others. But I did not know what career to choose. I saw people in school who did not deal with their problems well. Some people used bad ways to deal with their problems. This made me choose to study psychology. After I finished college in 2009, I took a break. One day, my friend introduced me to a 16-year-old boy who was scared. He was afraid of his parents. The next day, he called the police. I went to his parents' house to help. I told the police that I had studied psychology. They asked me to talk to the parents. I asked the parents about the boy's situation. They seemed nervous and made excuses.

This experience made me think about being a social worker. I want to help children like that boy who have family problems.

Another important value for social workers is fairness. Our society says that every person is important. But we also want to be like everyone else. I am an individual and I do not like to be the same as others. In school, I tried to make a difference. I wore colorful hair, wore clothes that showed my personality, and stood up for what I believe in. I am against unfairness and I will continue to fight against it.

This report explains the Biological and Sociocultural models for insomnia, a sleep disorder. The Biological model looks at genetics and medical health. The Sociocultural model examines the relationship between the environment and factors such as race, ethnicity, and socioeconomic status.

The report examines research on these models and explains each study. It then discusses the strengths and weaknesses of the research.

Insomnia is a sleep disorder that can be caused by different things. It can be a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental problem, or a sleep disorder caused by a medical condition or a substance. 

The primary sleep disorders include Dyssonmias and Parasomnias. Dyssonmias are problems with falling asleep or staying asleep. Parasomnias are sleep disorders that include behavioral and physical problems. Examples of Dyssonmias are Primary Insomnia and Primary Hypersomnia. Primary Insomnia is a problem with getting enough sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia is a problem with staying awake.

The Biological model of sleep disorders looks at genetics and how our bodies work. Research has shown that neurons in the brain called orexin help us sleep and wake up. A study on mice found that a receptor in the brain called GABAB helps us sleep. If this receptor is not working well, it can cause problems sleeping. The study found that a medicine called baclofen can help people sleep by activating the GABAB receptor.

The Sociocultural model of sleep disorders looks at how our environment affects our sleep. If the GABAB receptor is inherited, it can affect our sleep. This means that people may be more likely to have insomnia if their parents had it. This can have a big impact on our lives, especially when we have to do repetitive tasks and need to focus.

This paper talks about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, we will explain what CAPD is. Then, we will talk about how to diagnose the disorder. Finally, we will discuss how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) is a problem with how the brain uses sound. It is not a hearing problem. People with CAPD can hear sounds, but their brain has trouble understanding them. The brain has trouble separating sounds from background noise and understanding what people are saying.

The idea of CAPD was first talked about in the 1950s. Researchers were studying children with communication problems. They started giving tests to these children in 1954. In 1961, a researcher named Kimura created a test to understand how the brain works when we hear two sounds at the same time.

CAPD can cause several problems. A person with CAPD may have trouble finding the source of a sound. They may also have trouble hearing two or more sounds at the same time. It is hard for them to understand patterns in sounds. They may not be able to hear the difference in speech, like understanding sarcasm. Sometimes, one sound can cover up another sound. A person with CAPD may not be able to use sound clues to make sense of things. They may also have trouble understanding the order of sounds.

To diagnose CAPD, a doctor or specialist will watch how a person listens and reacts to sounds. They may also give tests to see how well the person can understand sounds. These tests may include questionnaires, watching how the person behaves, and measuring how well they can hear sounds in different situations. There is no one test that works for everyone, and we do not know what causes CAPD.

A teacher in a regular classroom can help a student with CAPD in several ways. First, they can give the student extra help understanding instructions. They can also give the student time to ask questions. Teachers can also try to reduce background noise in the classroom. This can help the student with CAPD focus on what the teacher is saying. Finally, teachers can work with the student to develop strategies to help them understand and use sound clues.

The play Twelfth Night says that pretending to be someone you are not can be useful for a short time, but in the end, you must be honest. If not, you could lose yourself forever. A big problem is that when you stop pretending, you may feel alone. This is because others may not understand why you tricked them. They may be angry with you. 

The play questions why people pretend to be someone else. In the play, the character Viola pretends to be a man to be safe from harm. She is good at pretending, and people believe her. But she also suffers. She cannot be with the women she knows, and she makes a man, Sebastian, fall in love with her. She also has feelings for the man Orsino, but she cannot tell him. 

The play shows how pretending can help people see their true feelings. For example, the woman Olivia loves Viola, who is pretending to be a man. But then she loves the real man Sebastian, who looks like Viola. This makes some people think that Olivia secretly loves women. But this may not be true. Olivia is probably just making fun of people who judge others based on how they look. 

The play says that we must be honest. We must be ourselves. Trying to be someone else can cause problems and hurt others. It is better to be true and be understood and loved for who you are.

The German colonial rule was very bad. It was especially bad for the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. The German colonial rule was not the same in all the colonies. It was different in policy and in how it was run. Education in the colonies was also different. When the British took over German East Africa in 1919, they found many Africans who could read and write. The German government in other colonies also worked to educate Africans.

But the situation in South West Africa was very different. The German government did not do much to educate the local people. Instead, missionary groups helped the local people. The government did help Europeans in the colony get an education. The government built schools for them and helped the missionary schools. The German government's decision had a big effect on South West Africa. Many years later, the country still had a lot of problems because of this.

Other German colonies had many educated and literate Africans. But in South West Africa, most people were not educated. They did not know how to read or write. Many things caused these problems in South West Africa. This paper wants to look at these things and learn more about the attitudes of the people in charge and the settlers.

There is a lot of writing about education in the German colonies. Most of these writings were in German and were written a long time ago. They described the education systems in the colonies. Later writings compared the education systems in different colonies. They looked at how the education systems were similar and different. One important study was done by Cohen. He compared education in South West Africa and East Africa. He said that the reason for the differences was because of the number of European settlers in South West Africa.

South West Africa had a good climate, but it had a lot of desert. The number of Europeans living there was not very big. In 1913, only about 15,000 Europeans lived in South West Africa. Many more Europeans lived in other German colonies. For example, only 5,336 Europeans lived in East Africa.

The kinds of music we call "pop music" have changed a lot over the last 100 years. Now we have many kinds of pop music. It is hard to make a complete list of all the kinds. Even the main kinds of pop music - like rock, country, jazz, and folk - have many smaller kinds within them.

One of the most interesting kinds of music is called Heavy Metal rock. It has a lot of emotions in it, mostly sad and dark feelings. But even though it is dark, people have made many different kinds of Heavy Metal music. They did this because it is very flexible and can be used in many ways.

Now, there are many different kinds of Heavy Metal music. They have taken ideas from other kinds of music and made them their own. But Heavy Metal music started from somewhere. To understand the music we hear today, we need to know what Heavy Metal music is and why it is called a "movement" rather than just a kind of music.

Heavy Metal music is often about darkness. It is music that is loud and strong. People who play Heavy Metal music are very good at playing their instruments. The music is different from other kinds of music because it is not simple. It has a lot of complicated parts.

Heavy Metal music also came from people who used drugs to help them create their music. In the 1970s, many people used drugs, and this led to some strange and new kinds of music. The music was like a reflection of the users' feelings, which were often sad and dark. Later, other people made music that was influenced by the dark feelings of the past. They took some of the ideas from the past and used them to make new music.

Some songs, like "Helter Skelter" by the Beatles, show the dark side of music. This song is considered one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to another song by the Rolling Stones, which was also very loud and dark. The Beatles wanted to show that they could make music as loud and dark as the Stones.

Henri Rousseau was a French artist. He lived from 1844 to 1910. Before the Surrealist artists made famous dreamlike paintings, Rousseau worked on his own dream-inspired art. His famous painting, The Dream, shows a woman looking at the wonders of a new place in her dream. But it also shows Rousseau's own hopes and dreams as an artist.

Rousseau wanted people to like and accept his art. He wanted to be famous and well-known. But he faced a big problem. He could either paint like other famous artists and follow the rules, or he could be different and do his own thing. This was a problem he had all his life.

To understand The Dream, you need to know about Rousseau's life. He was born in a town in northwest France. His father was a hardware dealer. Rousseau did not go to art school. He grew up and worked for the government until he was 40. After that, he started painting to make himself happy. He wanted to escape his sad life after his first wife died. He had eight baby children who also died. He had one daughter left, Julia.

Rousseau's art was different from other artists. He painted simple things and was a bit like a folk artist. He wanted to be accepted by the art world. But he had to compete with other famous artists like Matisse. Matisse was a talented artist who did not want to paint in a boring way. Rousseau, on the other hand, wanted to paint in a way that would make him famous.

Rousseau finally got recognition when he was older. But it was not until Matisse was already famous. A writer named Jan Gordon said that Rousseau's goal was to paint in a way that was safe and accepted by everyone. He wanted to be part of the French art group.

Many great thinkers believe that ethics and art are connected. They think that truth and beauty are closely related. I agree with this idea. A poet named John Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty." He said this in a poem about a special cup. He means that beauty and truth are the same thing. We learn many things in life from education and experience. But we like or dislike art and morals without being taught. Both ethics and aesthetics try to explain, not tell us what to do. We try to understand why a piece of art is beautiful or why an action is good, rather than following rules. 

We can't fully explain why something is good or beautiful. Critics of art or morals can't say exactly what makes something good. They might talk about things like how an artist uses color or background. But these things don't explain why something is good. When people talk about their favorite art or literature, they often say, "There's something about it." Then they give more details. I think that art and morals can't be explained completely. We can't say everything about why something is good or beautiful. A writer, Flannery O'Connor, said, "You tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." We tell a story to say something that can't be said in another way. I think ethics is the same. A philosopher, Wittgenstein, said, "Ethics can't be explained. Ethics is beyond words." I think that this "something" is what makes art and morality so powerful. It's this "something" that connects them.

I believe that ethics and art are closely related because they affect us deeply. We can't fully understand them, but we can feel them. This is especially true for literature. Literature is special because it deals with values. We learn values from literature, and that's why it's so important.

Germany is a strong country today. It is united with its own culture. This culture is from many different groups that lived in the area near the Alps in München to the city of Kiel on the Baltic Sea. You can feel the same culture in Köln on the Rhine River and in the city of Dresden on the Elbe River. This is not surprising because Germany's culture comes from many different sources, including old tribes.

The land of the Germans is called Germania. We do not know for sure how the name came to be. Some people think it came from a Germanic tribe. Others believe it came from the word for a spear, which the Germans used in war. It may also have come from an old Irish word that means "to shout." The Germans were known to be loud.

The Roman historian Tacitus wrote about the Germans in his book. He said that the Germans were an ancient group of people and not a mix of different groups. They were living in Germany when the Romans arrived. The Romans came to Germany to trade and to take things from the land. They also sent soldiers to fight in Germany, but they mostly went back to Rome.

The Germanic tribes began to appear in the first century. They lived near the Roman Empire and traded their goods. Some Germans also served in the Roman army.

I looked down and saw a picture in front of me. My mind was empty and not thinking about anything. I was watching the picture without feeling any strong emotions. My mind was working well, like a machine. I was looking at the picture, but I was not thinking about it in a special way.

I once got an art book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." An artist friend told me to get it. The book teaches people how to draw. It says to use a square to help you look at a picture. This helps you see the picture in a simple way. It makes the picture smaller and easier to understand.

I was looking at a bowl of fruit on a table. But I could not think of the square to put around the picture. I was too surprised. I stood and looked at the picture in wonder.

Some artists, like Picasso, like blue. Others, like Monet, like green. The old masters in Italy liked many colors. If I wanted to be a good artist, this was my chance. This was the start of my picture, my story, called "Work in Brown."

My hand moved to get a pencil. My hand moved to the toilet to draw. But my hand hit the toilet handle again and again. The brown package was stuck. I was very frustrated.

I held a mop, and I was thinking about the brown package. It was a waste of food. Someone had left it in the toilet at the Rite Aid store. I wanted it to go away. I wanted to clean it up.

I looked at the wall and took some toilet paper. My hand went into the toilet to try and get the package. I was careful, like a mom taking out a turkey for Thanksgiving.

Many young drivers die in car accidents.  Several things combine to cause this problem.  The National Institutes of Health say one reason is that young brains are not ready for the dangers of driving.  Young people also do not have much experience driving.  This lack of experience causes more car accidents and more severe injuries.  Teens do worse when they drive with their friends.  The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center studied this.  They found a connection between the age of the passenger and the number of car accidents.

California and other states try to make driving safer for young people.  They do this by giving temporary licenses that limit the hours young people can drive and do not allow other young passengers.

But these temporary licenses are not enough.  The real problem is that young people are not good at handling the risks and responsibilities of driving.  A psychologist named Marvin Zuckerman says 18 years old is too young for a regular driver's license.  He says young people under 19 or 20 often want to take risks because it is exciting.  This means we should delay giving driver's licenses to young teens.  If we do not, there will be more car accidents and the number of deaths will be very high.  By 2010, many new teen drivers will be on the road.

We can make a law to fix this problem.  Schools can teach driver's education classes.  But no one under 18 can drive a car.  A temporary permit can still be given before a full driver's license.  Young people must also get a certain number of hours of practice with a licensed driver.  The number of hours can be the same as the number of hours most states require.  A national law would be a good way to keep young people safe across the country.

This idea is not new.  But it can help save lives.

The Library of Congress has a collection of early Edison films. I looked through them. I found 15 trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing to create illusions. I studied these films to learn about their style and growth. Most trick films from this time are set in a fixed frame. The camera does not move to follow people or objects. The style comes from theater and vaudeville shows.

In some films, actors move side to side. They do not walk towards or away from the camera. An example is the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right and move back and forth.

The camera does not follow the actors when they leave the frame. Trick films usually show the whole scene at one time. They do not use close-up shots like we see in modern movies. This style comes from theater and vaudeville. The performers stay in the middle of the stage and do not move towards the camera.

Most early trick films show one scene at a time. This means they are usually short, only a minute or less. The films show simple tricks, like magic and disappearing acts. But sometimes, one scene is made up of many small parts. A good example is The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895). If you look closely, you can see where the camera starts to show Mary's head being cut off.

John Taylor of Caroline was a strong supporter of Republican ideas.  He was a farmer, but he also worked in politics.  These two things made him known for his strong opinions about personal freedom and government.  He believed that farming was the best job.  This idea influenced his thoughts about government.  He wanted to protect and help this kind of job.

Taylor thought the United States had a great chance to create a perfect system of government.  There was no old way of doing things to get in the way.  He believed in the basic rights of people.  These rights are like a team.  If one right is not fair, all the others are not good either.  He said the government should not control these rights.

Taylor said that some people with power and evil ideas would take advantage of others in nature.  But in a society, this should not happen.  To make a good society, the government must understand both good and bad in people.  Taylor thought government is like people.  It can be good or bad, depending on how it is run.

Taylor believed that a good government protects property, helps farming, and does not support capitalism.  He thought a good government would be fair, no matter who is in charge.  He believed that self-interest is a bad thing when it hurts others.  But it is not always bad.  A good government can keep this self-interest from making problems.

Taylor wanted the government to be limited.  He did not want the government to have more power than the Constitution said it could have.  He thought a big government would be expensive and could be cruel.  But he also thought a simple, strict reading of the Constitution could be bad.  Without understanding the ideas of the people who wrote it, this way of looking at the Constitution could be unfair.  Taylor thought the Declaration of Independence was more important than the Constitution.  It said that the United States is a group of states, not one country.

We look at Figure 17. There was a big drop in the number of people who used the commuter log in the third month of the project. This was not good news. It is hard to say why this happened. We know that winter came to the campus in New England. Fewer people ride bikes or walk during the winter. This might be one reason for the drop. Students and teachers were busy in December. They were finishing school and getting grades. They may have forgotten to fill out the log. December is also the start of the holiday time. Many students and teachers do not need to come to campus for a month. Classes start again in late January. This might also be a reason for the low number of logs. But we still do not know why there were few logs in February. People might get excited about a new project at the beginning. Then, their interest might decrease. We tried to make the project more interesting in March with the Carpool Challenge Week. We got more logs for that month. This shows that we need to find a way to keep people interested in the project. We also need to consider the fact that people like to drive cars. This is a part of our culture. We need to give people good reasons to use other ways of commuting. We gave prizes like gift cards to local stores. We gave out these prizes throughout the project. It would have been interesting to see if bigger prizes would have made more people participate. For example, if we had given away a bike or a new car, we might have gotten more people to use the commuter log. We did not change the prizes during the project. If we had said that we would give better prizes in the future, people might have been more interested.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a type of investment. It follows an index, a product, or a group of things like an index fund. But it is more flexible and trades like a stock on an exchange. You get the benefits of many investments and the ability to own a single stock. You can sell some, buy more, and buy as little as one share at a time. ETFs are also less expensive than mutual funds. But you must pay a fee for trading them. There are many different types of ETFs available.

We are looking at the ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings that make up 63.58% of its assets. We want to know if owning this one ETF is the same as owning a group of its top 10 stocks. We also want to know if there are better ways to invest in these same stocks.

To make it easier, we will only look at the top 10 holdings. Below, you can see the top 10 stocks and the percentage of the ETF's assets they make up.

We can use a chart to see how well these 10 stocks represent the ETF. We can use the percentages to calculate the returns and risk of a portfolio made up only of these 10 stocks. The chart shows the results.

The chart shows that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could get a 6.11% higher return than the ETF. It also shows that its risk is 0.12 lower. This means that owning just the top 10 holdings could be a good choice. But we need to be sure that the differences are real. To do this, we need to check the standard deviation of each stock. This will tell us if the differences are important or not.

Edgar Allan Poe wrote a poem called "Dream-Land". This is one of his good poems. He used a word "Thulé" in his poem. Poe said he got this word from the writer Virgil. Virgil used it to describe an island north of Britain. But Poe learned from another writer, Gothe. 

Gothe was a famous German writer. Poe liked his work. Gothe wrote a poem called "Faust". It was published in two parts. The second part came out after Gothe died in 1832. There is a short poem in "Faust" called "The King of Thulé". It is about a king who loses his wife. He drinks a lot and cries about his dead wife. He then decides to die. He gives away all his things, except a special cup. He goes to a cliff, throws the cup into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. Poe's poem "Dream-Land" is similar to "The King of Thulé". Maybe this is because Poe had lost someone and drank a lot like the king. 

Poe used the word Thule in two of his poems. He said "ultma Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum". He used it twice in "Dream-Land", at the beginning and the end. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be read together. In "Dream-Land", the speaker talks about a dark and lonely place called Thule. He sees dead friends and a world without color. This is like what happens in "The King of Thulé". The king is lonely because his wife died. He lost his will to rule or live. 

Gothe was a well-known writer. Poe would have read his work. Poe liked Tennyson, and Tennyson liked Gothe. Poe would have been interested in Gothe's work because of this connection.

A customer in California was hurt when she slipped and fell on applesauce in a store. The store manager, Martin, was informed about the spill twice, but he did not clean it. He was eating dinner at the time. Can this customer get extra money from the store for being hurt? The answer is yes. She can argue that the store manager should have known that not cleaning the spill would cause harm. Many people had slipped and fallen in the store before. 

To get extra money, the customer must show that the store manager acted on purpose and knew that his action would hurt someone. A court will not quickly reject her claim. The customer can say that the store manager should have cleaned the spill, even if it took some time. He should have known that not cleaning it would be a problem.

The store manager said he was busy eating dinner. But, he had been told about the spill twice. He ignored the problem. The customer slipped and fell 30 minutes later. This is not a good excuse. Many people had slipped and fallen in the store before, and the manager should have taken action.

California law says a customer can get extra money if the store manager acted with malice. Malice means the manager wanted to hurt someone or showed a bad disregard for the customer's safety. In this case, the customer can argue that the manager did not take the spill seriously and put many people in danger. 

The law in California says a court must consider if the store manager's actions were wrong and intended to cause harm. The customer can argue that the manager was aware that not cleaning the spill would cause harm and did not care. This is enough to make a claim for extra money.

In this case, six people slipped and fell in the store in one year. The manager did not take action to fix the problem. This is a good reason to argue that the manager acted with malice. He showed a bad disregard for the customers' safety.

In summary, the customer has a good chance to get extra money from the store for being hurt. She can argue that the store manager acted with malice and ignored the spill. This was a bad decision that put many people in danger.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam at CBC. A big question in the class was if Islam is a hostile religion. I think this question is still important today. Looking back at what happened since 9/11, I see that the media's view of Islam changed a great deal. From being very critical, it became more accepting. It's hard to believe that in 2001, a president with a Muslim background like Barack Obama could have run for office.

I'm interested in the story of the Prophet Muhammad. What I learned about him seems different from his personality. I thought he forced people to become Muslims. He would win battles and then make the defeated tribes join his religion. But his story says he was a humble and kind man. He didn't try to prove himself, but lived a simple life with miracles. This makes me think the writers wanted people to see him as a special person, but it takes away from the legend of Jesus.

There are many stories in the biography that seem like they are trying to show how people believed in Muhammad on their own. But the problem is that many of these stories come from people who heard from others. This makes the stories seem less real. I don't like this because it makes it seem like they are trying to hide the truth.

I have a big problem with the way the biography presents Muhammad. It says he was a kind and wise man, but history shows that he was not. I wonder if Muslims know the real story of how he became powerful.

The ideas of Jesus were not kept after he died. The Christian way of thinking changed quickly. If we look at the past, we see that Christianity moved away from its roots. Today, we see a growing understanding and a new way of thinking. Many traditional people will not change. They will not accept new ideas. But they are not the majority. More and more people will be interested in the real meaning of Christianity. In the future, many people will want to know what Jesus truly said. They will want to separate the ideas added to Christianity over time from the true meaning of the religion. It may take time, but this will happen. Christianity will go back to its original form. A movement will start to remove extra ideas. It will be like going back in time. Only the ideas of Jesus will be left. When this happens in the United States and Europe, many people will follow Jesus' ideas as if they lived in his time. The church will remain strong to guide people. But the church will be more simple. There will be less difference between different groups. People will be more alike in what they believe. This is not the first time this has happened. The Roman Empire persecuted Christians, but later became Christian. Our country has changed from slave to leader. The same thing will happen in the Christian church. People will go back to the source. They will not care about different groups and ideas. To make this happen, people will start to understand Jesus' words as examples, not as real things. If we look far back in time, we only see Judaism. This is the base of the Christian religion. The idea of one god, the power of the Bible, and the authority of Jewish leaders were all important parts of Judaism before the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish people were not all the same. They had different groups like Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and many common people.

The Jungle shows that people are naturally selfish and only think about themselves. They want to make their lives better, but they do not care about others. The book shows this in many ways. One example is the owners and managers of big factories. They only want to make their companies bigger and better. They do not care about anything that gets in their way or gets hurt. They do not care about the air pollution or the dirty water from the factory animals. 

The owners and managers also do not care about their workers. They pay them very little and make them work long hours. They can fire workers without warning and without giving them any help finding a new job. During that time, there were no laws to protect workers. This meant the owners and managers could do what they wanted. The workers lived and worked in bad conditions. They did not have any help or information about their rights. Some workers formed unions, but they often made money from the poor workers. The workers were treated very badly and had no way to escape the system.

The Jungle says that people in this situation are like slaves. They are poor and do not have many opportunities. They depend on the owners and managers for their lives. That means they have to do what they are told, even if it is bad for them. The book says that in this situation, bad behavior is common and expected.

F. Scott Fitzgerald uses different methods to make readers feel a certain way about important things. He
uses many of these methods in his novel The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, Fitzgerald pairs words together
to make a new meaning. He uses this to give a special feeling around a subject. Fitzgerald also uses
symbols and gives them meaning. Then he uses the same symbol for the same feeling. He does this with
many colors, like gold, green, white, gray, red, and pink.

Fitzgerald uses white and gray to show sameness. White means nice and high class, but gray means old
and faded. He starts to show this in the beginning of the novel. He uses these colors many times. Daisy
and Jordan wear white all the time. Nick wears white clothes to Gatsby's party. Tom wears a white shirt
when he meets Myrtle. Fitzgerald uses these colors on many ordinary things, like a white chasm in New
York, gray cars, and gray land.

After he shows the meaning of white and gray, he uses them to show that something is not important.
He starts with Daisy. He does not use these colors for a long time, and then he describes Daisy as wearing
white. This shows that Daisy is not a special character, but just someone Gatsby wants.

Fitzgerald uses this technique again to show that Daisy is not special. For example, he describes her fur
collar as gray and her dress as white. He wants readers to see Daisy as just another person, not as a
special person.

San Diego County is a good place for growing food. The climate is mild and sunny. People grow many foods there. These include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy green vegetables, squash, broccoli, herbs, fruits like peaches and lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Many people in the area want to buy organic food from local farms. Some farmers have long waiting lists for their community-supported agriculture programs. People also buy organic eggs and milk from these farmers.

Some of these farms allow visitors to see how they grow food. People can also walk, hike, or watch birds on the farms. This helps the farmers make extra money and teach others about their work.

Organic farming is good for the environment. It helps plants and animals in the area. This is because it does not use chemicals in the soil and water. But organic farming can be more expensive than farming with chemicals. It needs more work and management to stop pests and weeds and make the soil healthy without chemicals. Organic farms also have higher losses than big farms that use chemicals. 

The land chosen for this project is near the town of Potrero in San Diego County. It is 160 acres of land with chaparral, grass, and oak trees. The area is near the Cleveland National Forest. Many animals live there. Some are endangered and need our help. The area was once home to Native Americans and later to cattle ranchers and people who sold wood.

I chose this land from a website and looked at government programs that can help small farmers. I found a real farm in the area that grows organic food. This farm is a model for what a farmer in the area might do to make a living and help the environment.

Culture is very important in negotiations. It is not easy to define culture. It is not the same everywhere. Culture is not just one thing. We should not say that all people from a certain country are the same. For example, we should not say, "All Russians are stubborn" or "All Japanese are very polite." It is better to understand the culture of a country and how it affects a negotiation.

When we go to a new country, we see their culture in a way that makes sense to us. We make comparisons with our own culture. To understand a foreign culture, we can learn about its history or its problems. We should not judge or try to change their culture. We should accept it and work with it. This is especially true when we are in a weaker position in a negotiation.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies also have their own cultures. A company's culture can be very different from another company's culture. Some companies work very hard, while others have a more relaxed schedule. We can see a company's culture in the way its employees dress, communicate, and work. Some companies want their employees to help others, but others do not.

Values are very important to understand. They explain why people behave in certain ways. If people in a culture value saving face or being kind to each other, they will not do things that might hurt others. If people value hard work, they will try to get a good deal in a negotiation. We should think about these values before we start a negotiation. But we should also try to understand our opponent on a personal level to be successful in a negotiation.

The Bible says, "The fool says in his heart, 'There is no God.'" This idea is from Psalm 14. A Christian philosopher named St. Anselm used this idea in his argument about God's existence. We will also discuss Thomas Aquinas, who also believed in God. Both of their ideas are about the same God in the Bible. To compare their ideas, let's assume that they are both right.

St. Anselm's idea is that God exists in our minds. He says we can know God exists because we can think about God. This idea is based on faith. Faith is believing in something without proof.

St. Thomas Aquinas has a different idea. He says we can know God exists by using our reason and looking at the world around us. We do not need faith. He gives five reasons for God's existence. These reasons are change, cause, chance, perfection, and order. He says these reasons show that we need God. For example, imagine you have a puzzle with most of the pieces. If you know the whole picture, you can know what the missing piece is like.

In this way, St. Aquinas says we can know God exists using our minds and what we see in the world.

Buddha was born in the fifth or sixth century BCE. He was a prince. Later in life, he gave up his position in the world and became a wise man. This man's teachings led to the creation of Buddhism. One part of Buddhism is called Theravada Buddhism. This religion is about 2,500 years old. It is different from what it was when Buddha was alive. You can see these changes in Theravada countries like Sri Lanka.

In Sri Lanka, a yearly ceremony is held. It is called the water-cutting ceremony. Monks and ordinary people take part in this ceremony. But Buddha never taught about a ceremony like this. These changes are not only in small things. They are in the main ideas of the religion too.

The Theravada Buddhist community has changed its ideas over time. This happened both from inside and outside the community. Inside the community, changes came from people who are Buddhist. Outside the community, changes came from people who are not Buddhist. Changes that are good for the community are called benign. Changes that are bad for the community are called hostile.

To understand this better, we need to know some key ideas. 

Internal means something that comes from inside the Buddhist community. External means something that comes from outside the community. Hostile means something that hurts the community. Benign means something that does not hurt the community, even if it has a bad effect.

Now, let's look at the main ideas of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists believe in three important things: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is a collection of Buddhist teachings. It includes three groups of books: the Sutta Pitaka, the Vinaya Pitaka, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka.

The Sutta Pitaka has teachings that are like conversations. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for Buddhist monks and nuns. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about the universe. Some of these ideas are that everything is not permanent, that life is hard, and that people have no soul.

To end the cycle of death and rebirth, people must understand these ideas. They must also understand that desire, hatred, and confusion are the causes of suffering. To stop suffering, people must give up these things. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for lay Buddhists. These rules say do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not be lazy, and do not take drugs. Monks have more rules to follow.

The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. The first truth is that life is suffering. The second truth is that attachment causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can be ended.

The United States and Mexico are two countries with a long history of rivalry. This rivalry lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The two countries had many fights. The biggest fight was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. The United States won this war and got Texas and the American Southwest. 

The rivalry began because of disagreements about religion, culture, and tradition. The two countries had different ideas about these things. They also had big problems with material goods. The United States and Mexico are not the only countries that have a big rivalry with a neighbor. Many countries that share a border have problems like this.

David M. Pletcher says, "Only in Mexico and Cuba do we find long-lasting American diplomatic problems." Both Mexico and Cuba are close to the United States. They have been rivals to the United States for a long time. Other countries in Latin America have good relations with the United States.

Religion was a big problem between the two countries. The United States and Mexico had different ideas about what is right. This has been a problem for many countries throughout history. Sally Frahm says, "If Americans were against fascism and communism in the twentieth century, they were against Catholicism and monarchy in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries." The United States and Mexico had a rivalry based on their different ideas about religion. This was because of the distrust between the English and Spanish.

The United States and Mexico had many problems. They had 17 fights between 1836 and 1893. Most of these fights were about territory and border problems. Outlaws and bandits from the United States had problems on the border. This was a big problem until both countries used their military to control the border.

The rivalry between the United States and Mexico ended as Mexico became dependent on the United States. The United States changed its goals from expanding its territory to helping Mexico economically. This change happened in the later part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I got sick. I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen nursing because I wanted a safe and secure job. Many people told me that nursing was a good job because people will always get sick. 

But I had bigger dreams. I wanted to be a scientist or a journalist. However, I chose nursing. I am now 61 years old and unable to work. I get money from Social Security, but I have no savings. Every day is a struggle.

I have been lucky because my family and some friends have helped me. But when something bad happens, you feel very weak. 

My point is that life is full of emergencies. We cannot be sure of the future. We need to be prepared, but some problems are too big for one person to solve alone.

I agree that we should not rely too much on big government. But I think we should try to trust each other more. We should help each other and ask for help when we need it. 

Some people say that America was built on rugged individualism. But it was really about helping each other and sharing what we have. The people who traveled across the country in wagons did not do it alone. They worked together.

So, be prepared. I have a disaster kit and first aid supplies. I also have food and water for a long time. If you have a big piece of land, you can grow your own food and store it for later. This is a good idea. But it is also important to know your neighbors.

Why do living things change over time? Are there rules that guide the way they change? Many scientists have tried to understand this, but it is still a hard problem. Recently, some scientists have used math to study how animals grow and change. They looked at the shells of a certain type of animal called Prunum. The scientists want to know how these animals change over time and how their shells develop. They used special pictures of the shells to create math models. These models can help them understand how the animals' shells grow and change. The scientists also did experiments to learn more about the animals and their shells.

A shell is like a tube that moves through space over time. It turns around in a circle, like a spiral. This spiral is divided into parts called whorls. Each whorl is like a ring that grows as the animal gets older. The whorls turn around a middle line that runs through the shell. This line is called the columella. The speed at which the whorls grow can be different, and a line separates each whorl. This line is called a suture. The last whorl of the shell is the biggest one. The spire is all the whorls except the last one. The tip of the spire is called the apex, and the other end is called the base. The animal comes out of its shell through a hole called the aperture.

We can look at shells in different ways. We can look at the top, the bottom, the front, or the back. Most of the time, we look at the front of the shell. When we look at the shell from the front, the aperture is open, and the apex is pointing up.

To measure the whorls, we look at the shell from the top and find where the first line is. Then we draw a line to divide the shell. We count the whorls from this line, and we can estimate the number of whorls to one-quarter of a whorl.

A shell is like a path that the animal follows as it grows. We can trace this path by looking at the center of each whorl and the size of the aperture. We can draw this path and use math to understand how the animal's shell grows. Once we have a math formula, we can change the parameters and see how the shell would grow differently.

Indonesia's rate of death for newborn babies and infants has not improved much in the last ten years.  The country is doing well in some areas, like making clean water and sanitation available.  But the country is not making good progress in improving health for mothers and children.  Indonesia is not meeting its goals for improving health by 2015.  There are many reasons for this.  They will be explained below.

Indonesia has made some progress in the number of births where a health worker is present.  Now, 72% of births have a worker like a nurse or a midwife.  But this does not mean all of these workers can give medical help if a mother or baby gets sick.  Many mothers and babies still die from bleeding during delivery.  This means the progress made in this area is not really very good.  Indonesia's health department also has a problem with treating children under five who have diarrhea.  Many children in the country do not get help from a health worker.  The country also does not have good records about taking care of mothers after they give birth.

Many mothers do not have a cesarean operation when they need it.  In fact, only 4% of mothers have this operation.  The number of cesarean operations is higher in cities than in villages.  This shows that many people in villages do not have access to healthcare.  Many people can not afford healthcare because they have to pay out of their own money.  This is a big problem in Indonesia.

To improve health for mothers and babies, the government needs to decide what to do.  One idea is to help with specific programs for mothers and babies.  But this might not be the best idea.  Programs that focus on one area of health can be more effective and give faster results.  But they can also have some problems.  One problem is that they might take money and workers away from other areas of healthcare.  Another problem is that many programs can cause confusion and extra work.

Victorian novels often look at small details. But two books, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have mystery and strange things that are not common in other Victorian novels. This makes the characters more interesting and helps us understand their thoughts and feelings.

One time, Oliver Twist had many confusing ideas in his mind. He was walking with two men, Sikes and Crackit, who were arguing. Oliver thought he was still with them, but then he heard gunshots and people shouting. He felt pain and was taken away. This happened many times, and Oliver felt scared and in pain.

Oliver's dreams or strange times like these often tell us something about his feelings and problems. In one chapter, Oliver remembers being shot. He relives the moment like it's a dream. This shows how Oliver had no control over what happened to him. He was in a lot of pain and was taken away without knowing what was happening.

Oliver's life is hard. He has little control over things. He can't even try to take care of himself when his life is in danger. This makes us think that Oliver gives up easily. Maybe someone else is controlling him, making him feel this way.

Another time, Oliver says, "The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours." This means that time goes by quickly when you are in a bad situation. Oliver feels like he is trapped in a long night that is not ending.

I worked in an after-school program two years ago. I helped students who needed help in different subjects. But my strengths were in English and reading. One boy, Adrian, had trouble reading. He was in third or fourth grade. I think he was having a big problem. Some letters he could read well, but not others. This was strange.

Adrian spoke perfect English, but I learned that his mother did not speak English. She spoke only Spanish. I know a little Spanish, but not much. We talked a little. Then I understood the problem. Adrian could read, but he did not know the English alphabet well.

I share this story to talk about the problem of language barriers in schools. Even students who speak good English can still have trouble reading. I think everyone agrees this is a problem. What can we do? For Adrian, the answer was simple. He needed help with reading and the alphabet.

But for students who do not speak much English, the answer is not simple. There is no one solution. We need to try many things. These are bilingual education, English as a Second Language (ESL) classes, and private tutors. We need to use all of these things together.

One good idea is bilingual education. This is when students learn in two languages. This helps students do well in school. Some people are afraid of this idea. They think it is a waste of money and that most students will not benefit. But this is not true. If we used this idea in all schools, all students would benefit.

How can we make this happen? Do we need all teachers to speak two languages? No, this would be hard. But we can have special helpers who speak two languages. These helpers can work with students who need extra help.

Most of us learn as children that there is something bigger than us.  We may go to Sunday school or the Temple to learn about it.  Some people search for answers inside themselves.  Many people accept the religion their parents teach.  But some people reject it.  They do not believe there is something beyond what they know.  We may change our minds and choose a different way.  Every person chooses a path to understand spirituality in their own way.  We look for a light in the dark to guide us.

I asked my father about his favorite bird one day.  We were on our front porch, listening to the rain.  He stared out into the rain.  He looked thin and tired.  His hair was thinning.  I felt sad and afraid.  I didn't want to talk about how much I would miss him.  I hugged him and sat close to him.  We looked out into the rain together.

My father died in December.  He had cancer.  The doctors tried to make him feel better, but it was not easy.  He suffered for a few more months than the doctors said he would.  I could not understand why he had to suffer so much.  If God existed, I thought, he was not listening to me.

I did not want to watch my father die.  I wanted to remember how he lived, not how he died.  I wanted my father to be happy, not sad and weak.  I curled up in bed for three days and waited for the news.  No one called me to tell me about my father's death.

The Gothic Novel is called an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'" by Ian Watt. This means it is a mix of old and new things. The Gothic style has been both praised and criticized. Some people think it has no real meaning, while others say it is powerful and exciting. The first Gothic Novel was written by Horace Walpole. He combined old ideas from medieval times with new ideas from modern novels. This created a new way of writing.

Horace Walpole's book, The Castle of Otranto, used old theatrical ideas and new ways to write about nature. He called it "A Gothic Story." The Gothic style uses old ideas from medieval times, like theater and architecture. Many people thought the word "gothic" was old-fashioned and not sophisticated. But the combination of old and new made the Gothic style stay popular for a long time.

One important idea in Gothic novels is chivalry. Chivalry is a set of rules for knights to follow. It includes being brave, honorable, and strong. Gothic writers liked this idea because it showed a perfect person. They wanted to show how society was not perfect and that we need to be better. The writer of The Castle of Otranto, Horace Walpole, was worried about the future. He thought the world was not a good place. He used the idea of chivalry to show how we should be better. The main character, Frederic, is a prince who has suffered a lot. He is brave, kind, and strong like a knight. This is an example of how the Gothic style uses old ideas to make a new kind of story.
